[ ] CLI output projects by shape and destination $The CLI is a thin projection over graphd with two orthogonal axes. Shape picks the structured format because topology drives serialization: list views become ndjson (one record per line), tree views become nested json, graph views become triples or jsonld. Destination picks render versus emit: a terminal renders the human view (table, indented tree, graph summary) while a pipe emits the structured format. Explicit json, ndjson, and jsonld flags override both axes. The CLI never parses graph formats and holds no sparql or prefixes; the view shape comes from graphd registry.$ !2 #019f76ca-f3b1-7613-a0de-74f453f8576c
[-] graphd becomes a standalone tool $Make graphd usable directly by humans and agents, not just the CLI. It self-discovers config via core instead of receiving it in the request envelope, and owns a named-query registry where each entry carries a name, its sparql, and a declared shape (list, tree, or graph). It owns output modes (rows, ndjson, nested json, jsonld) behind a clean argument interface. The CLI consumes this same public interface, not a private protocol. Someone can install graphd without the CLI. Drop the config field from the stdin request once self-discovery lands.$ !2 #019f76cb-c2f7-7741-9153-1312f4d15d33
[ ] Rescope query output spec to graphd semantic contract $Query output specification was written when the graph lived in core, so it claimed one payload for every consumer. Rescope it: the spec governs graphd semantic jsonld output and the federation contract where meaning travels with the data. Document the CLI presentation contract separately, including the shape taxonomy (list to ndjson, tree to nested json, graph to triples) and the terminal versus pipe axis. The meaning-travels principle still holds for the semantic layer.$ !3 #019f77b2-d6d0-7193-acb8-3c54563cf27c
